\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Kinetic representation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We consider a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $d+1$
\end_inset

 (or more) kinetic velocities 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{k}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0\ldots d$
\end_inset

, associated to 
\series bold
vectorial
\series default
 kinetic functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{k}(W)\in\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 The macroscopic data are related to the kinetic data by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=\sum_{k}F_{k}.
\]

\end_inset

We also define 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Maxwellian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 equilibrium functions 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{k}(W)\in\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=\sum_{k}M_{k}(W).
\]

\end_inset

The kinetic BGK representation is given by transport equations with relaxation
 source terms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bouchut1999construction,aregba2000discrete"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{t}F_{k}+V_{k}\cdot\nabla_{X}F_{k}=\frac{1}{\tau}\left(M_{k}(W)-F_{k}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Kinetic representation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
When the relaxation time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\to0^{+}$
\end_inset

, the kinetic model is formally equivalent to the initial system of conservation
 laws if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=\sum_{k}M_{k}(W),\quad\sum_{k}V_{k}^{i}M_{k}(W)=Q^{i}(W),\quad i=1,\ldots,d.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Linear system of size 
\begin_inset Formula $m(d+1)\times m(d+1)$
\end_inset

 for finding the Maxwellian.
 One expects a unique solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In practice it is difficult to solve directly the BGK system.
 A splitting is preferable.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Kinetic algorithm
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Start with 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\cdot,0)$
\end_inset

.
 Construct kinetic vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{k}(\cdot,0)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\sum_{k}F_{k}$
\end_inset

 (not unique);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
solve the free transport equations 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}F_{k}+V_{k}^{i}\cdot\partial_{i}F_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for a duration of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

.
 This gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{k}(X,\Delta t^{-})=F_{k}(X-\Delta tV_{k},0);
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W(\cdot,\Delta t)=\sum_{k}F_{k}(\cdot,\Delta t^{-});
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
apply a relaxation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{k}(\cdot,\Delta t^{+})=\omega M_{k}(W(\cdot,\Delta t))+(1-\omega)F_{k}(\cdot,\Delta t^{-}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interesting cases: 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is a matrix.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Flux error representation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
During the computations, one expects that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}V_{k}^{i}F_{k}\simeq Q^{i}(W)$
\end_inset

, we thus introduce the 
\series bold
approximated flux 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

, 
\series default
and the 
\series bold
flux error 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset


\series default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z^{i}=\sum_{k}V_{k}^{i}F_{k},\quad Y^{i}=Z^{i}-Q^{i}(W).
\]

\end_inset

The kinetic algorithm is then a functional operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}(\Delta t)$
\end_inset

 that maps 
\begin_inset Formula $(W(\cdot,0),Y^{i}(\cdot,0))$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(W(\cdot,\Delta t),Y^{i}(\cdot,\Delta t^{+}))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is made of (linear) shift operations and (non-linear) local relaxations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the 
\begin_inset Formula $(W,Y^{i})$
\end_inset

 variables, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=2$
\end_inset

, the relaxation operation simply reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y^{i}(\cdot,\Delta t^{+})=-Y^{i}(\cdot,\Delta t^{-}).
\]

\end_inset

This induces fast oscillations of the flux error.
 For the analysis it is better to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\circ\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Equivalent equation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
In principle it is now easy, while tedious, to compute the equivalent equation
 of the kinetic algorithm: simply compute a Taylor expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mathcal{M}(\Delta t/2)-\mathcal{M}(-\Delta t/2)}{\Delta t}
\]

\end_inset

with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 up to order 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\Delta t^{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The term 
\begin_inset Formula $X-\Delta tV_{k}$
\end_inset

 in the shift operation generates partial derivatives in space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Because of symmetries, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=2$
\end_inset

, the even order terms vanish.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
And finally, the relaxation introduce non linearities.
 We end up with a system of non-linear conservation laws of first order
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $(W,Y^{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
One-dimensional case
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We consider the case 
\begin_inset Formula $d=1$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d+1=2$
\end_inset

 kinetic velocities.
 We take 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}=-\lambda$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}=\lambda$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $W=F_{0}+F_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The equivalent equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=2$
\end_inset

 at order 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\Delta t^{2})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{t}W+\partial_{x}Q(W)=0,
\]

\end_inset

(of course) and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{t}Y-d_{W}Q(W)\partial_{x}Y=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We observe that the system is hyperbolic and that the waves for 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 move in opposite direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No assumption of smallness of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is necessary to analyze the third order terms to find the sub-characteristic
 stability condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda\geq\max_{1\leq i\leq m}\left|\lambda_{i}(W)\right|,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(W)$
\end_inset

 are the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{W}Q(W)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Two-dimensional case
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We consider the case 
\begin_inset Formula $d=2$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d+1=3$
\end_inset

 kinetic velocities.
 We take 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{k}=\lambda\left(\begin{array}{c}
\cos\frac{2k\pi}{3}\\
\sin\frac{2k\pi}{3}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The equivalent equation on 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=2$
\end_inset

 at order 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\Delta t^{2})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{t}W+\partial_{1}Q^{1}(W)+\partial_{2}Q^{2}(W)=0,
\]

\end_inset

(of course).
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{i}(W)=d_{W}Q^{i}(W)$
\end_inset

, the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\partial_{t}\left(\begin{array}{c}
Y_{1}\\
Y_{2}
\end{array}\right)+\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{\lambda}{2}I-A^{1}(W) & 0\\
-A^{2}(W) & -\frac{\lambda}{2}
\end{array}\right)\partial_{1}\left(\begin{array}{c}
Y_{1}\\
Y_{2}
\end{array}\right)+\\
\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & -\frac{\lambda}{2}I-A^{1}(W)\\
-\frac{\lambda}{2} & -A^{2}(W)
\end{array}\right)\partial_{2}\left(\begin{array}{c}
Y_{1}\\
Y_{2}
\end{array}\right) & =O(\Delta t^{2}),
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

We can prove that the equivalent system is symmetrizable, and thus hyperbolic,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is large enough (sub-characteristic condition).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
